    <title>Combined summary - 0.4rc1 known bugs</title>
    <updated>2023-06-04T18:54:13.263191+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2011-September/000450.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In September 2011, multiple issues were reported with Bitcoin's code. Gavin Andresen provided an update on version 0.4 and suggested tracking down deadlocks to become more familiar with the code. Sipa found a deadlock between the addr-handling and IRC-join-handling code and proposed a solution by adding CRITICAL_BLOCK before addrDB.TxnBegin(). UukGoblin reported a deadlock problem on a bitcoind handling getwork requests. ArtForz discovered a performance bug concerning transactions with thousands of inputs and outputs on the solidcoin test network.Michael Grønager discovered that the UPNP feature was not disabled by default and made changes in the makefile.unix file to avoid any issues. He later reported his findings after performing a quick compile and run of bitcoind on Ubuntu 10.04.3 LTS, mentioning that he did not use the UPNP feature but had to change the USE_UPNP setting in makefile.unix to avoid any issues. Michael also apologized for his mistake and offered to clean up interfaces and classes to enhance the code's flexibility and move towards a more library/interface-like split.Pieter Wuille reported deadlock issues while using DEBUG_LOCKORDER, but later realized they were not actual potential deadlocks. Detective Wuille was praised for his successful patch for the cs_mapaddresses deadlock issue in Bitcoin's code. He reviewed all places initiating a database transaction to ensure there were no similar issues. Luke-Jr reported a fix for the encrypted-wallet mining issue, which was reviewed but not yet tested. He suggested the use of unique_coinbase and created a test plan, including running a clean testnet-in-a-box bitcoind with -keypool=1 and encrypting the wallet.In conclusion, various issues were reported with Bitcoin's code in September 2011, and the developers worked to find solutions and improve the code's functionality and flexibility.</summary>
